<subSubSection id="C35436B80B30FFFDFF2DBD899745AA38" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B30FFFDFF2DBD8993CAAEA8" blockId="33.[136,1452,158,545]" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B30FFFDFF2DBD899720AF80" bold="true" box="[189,353,158,184]" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Discussion:—</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B30FFFDFEF1BD8997BEAF80" author="Franck, R. A. &amp; Barrios, D. &amp; Campbell, K. &amp; Lange, J. &amp; Peguero, B. &amp; Santiago-Valentin, E. &amp; Rigerszki, Z. &amp; Haakonsson, J. &amp; Gann, G. &amp; Cinea, W. &amp; Howe, N. &amp; John, J. &amp; Moreno, J. &amp; Clark, C." box="[353,511,158,184]" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" pagination="129 - 182" refId="ref16698" refString="Franck, R. A., Barrios, D., Campbell, K., Lange, J., Peguero, B., Santiago-Valentin, E., Rigerszki, Z., Haakonsson, J., Gann, G., Cinea, W., Howe, N., John, J., Moreno, J. &amp; Clark, C. (2019) Revision of Pilosocereus (Cactaceae) in the Caribbean and northern Andean region. Phytotaxa 411: 129 - 182. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 411.3.1" type="journal article" year="2019">Franck (2019)</bibRefCitation>
considered the plants on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B30FFFDFC83BD89953CAF80" box="[787,893,158,184]" name="Barbados" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Barbados</collectingCountry>
to be 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B30FFFDFC2DBD8992E0AF80" authorityName="Franck" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Otto" box="[957,1185,158,184]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Pilosocereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="curtisii">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B30FFFDFC2DBD8992E0AF80" box="[957,1185,158,184]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Pilosocereus curtisii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, based on our observations, the 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B30FFFDFEDBBDD597F4AFE4" box="[331,437,194,220]" name="Barbados" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Barbados</collectingCountry>
plants should be treated as a distinct, although closely related, taxa. We cannot discount the possibility that 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B30FFFDFEA5BDF0979BAE38" authorityName="Byles &amp; Rowley" authorityYear="1957" baseAuthorityName="Britton &amp; Rose" box="[309,474,230,256]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Pilosocereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="barbadensis">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B30FFFDFEA5BDF0979BAE38" box="[309,474,230,256]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">P. barbadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is identical to plants found elsewhere in the Lesser Antilles, or that plants intermediate with 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B30FFFDFF2FBC1C9769AE1C" authorityName="Franck" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Otto" box="[191,296,267,292]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Pilosocereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="curtisii">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B30FFFDFF2FBC1C9769AE1C" box="[191,296,267,292]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">P. curtisii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exist. If this species is distinct, then it becomes a 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B30FFFDFCD7BC1D95F0AE1C" box="[839,945,266,292]" name="Barbados" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Barbados</collectingCountry>
endemic, having a very restricted distribution area and hence of conservation concern. We observed that many plants have been damaged by burning and are under threat due to land use change. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B30FFFDFE7EBC4594A6AE54" author="Maycock, J. D." box="[494,743,338,364]" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" refId="ref17739" refString="Maycock, J. D. (1830) Flora Barbadensis. James Ridgway, London, 446 pp." type="book" year="1830">Maycock (1830: 202)</bibRefCitation>
used the misapplied name 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B30FFFDFBB6BC449344AE54" box="[1062,1285,338,365]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Cereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="monoclonos">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B30FFFDFBB6BC449344AE54" box="[1062,1285,338,365]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Cereus monoclonos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for this plant. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B30FFFDFF18BC619729AEA9" author="Hughes, G." box="[136,360,374,401]" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" refId="ref17166" refString="Hughes, G. (1750) The Natural History of Barbados. Published by the author, London, 314 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 47069" type="book" year="1750">Hughes (1750: 135)</bibRefCitation>
describes a plant he calls “The American Torch, Lat. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B30FFFDFC51BC61924EAEA8" box="[961,1039,374,400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Cereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Cereus</taxonomicName>
maximus.”, which is this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B30FFFDFF2DBC8D92E7AD18" blockId="33.[136,1452,158,545]" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">
Compared to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B30FFFDFECFBC8D940BAE8C" authorityName="Franck" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Otto" box="[351,586,410,436]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Pilosocereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="curtisii">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B30FFFDFECFBC8D940BAE8C" box="[351,586,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Pilosocereus curtisii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B30FFFDFDCDBC8C9547AE8C" authorityName="Byles &amp; Rowley" authorityYear="1957" baseAuthorityName="Britton &amp; Rose" box="[605,774,410,436]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Pilosocereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="barbadensis">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B30FFFDFDCDBC8C9547AE8C" box="[605,774,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">P. barbadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has thicker stems, usually more ribs and a much greater difference between flowering and non-flowering areoles (
<figureCitation id="137579B60B30FFFDFC82BCA995DCAEE1" box="[786,925,446,473]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 35" captionStart-1="FIGURE 36" captionStart-2="FIGURE 37" captionStartId-0="35.[136,229,1953,1975]" captionStartId-1="36.[136,229,1953,1975]" captionStartId-2="37.[136,229,1772,1794]" captionTargetBox-0="[213,1374,190,1929]" captionTargetBox-1="[213,1374,190,1929]" captionTargetBox-2="[151,1436,190,1747]" captionTargetId-0="figure-17@35.[213,1374,190,1929]" captionTargetId-1="figure-21@36.[213,1374,190,1929]" captionTargetId-2="figure-17@37.[151,1436,190,1747]" captionTargetPageId-0="35" captionTargetPageId-1="36" captionTargetPageId-2="37" captionText-0="FIGURE 35. Non-flowering stem of Pilosocereus barbadensis (Hoxey 1705.01)." captionText-1="FIGURE 36. Flowering stem of Pilosocereus barbadensis (Hoxey 1708.01). Flowering areoles have dense tuft of hairs, with more numerous and much longer spines." captionText-2="FIGURE 37. Pilosocereus barbadensis (Hoxey 1705.01). A comparison of flowering (top) and non-flowering (below) areoles." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420373" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420375" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420377" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5420373/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5420375/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/5420377/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Figs. 35–37</figureCitation>
). The flowering areoles often form on just one side of the stem in three or four ribs. We only observed flowers on the mature areoles (
<figureCitation id="137579B60B30FFFDFBE4BCF59286AEC4" box="[1140,1223,482,508]" captionStart="FIGURE 38" captionStartId="38.[136,229,1072,1094]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1048]" captionTargetId="figure-21@38.[151,1436,190,1048]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 38. Pilosocereus barbadensis (Hoxey 1708.01) in flower." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420379" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420379/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
) and never juvenile areoles. A comparison of characteristics of the two 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B30FFFDFD55BF1195ECAD18" box="[709,941,518,544]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Pilosocereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="33" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B30FFFDFD55BF119514AD18" box="[709,853,518,544]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Pilosocereus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
is outlined in 
<tableCitation id="C6CC50880B30FFFDFBDCBF1192E3AD18" box="[1100,1186,518,544]" captionStart="TABLE 6" captionStartId="33.[136,224,592,616]" captionText="TABLE 6. A comparison of Pilosocereus curtisii and Pilosocereus barbadensis." pageId="33" pageNumber="58">Table 6</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
